Memphis Business Journal







Related Content
            





                            Memphis startups tapped for regional network                        





                            Conversation With…Esra Roan of SOMAVAC Medical Solutions                        





                            FedEx-backed startup accelerator now taking applications                        



 



 











 Enlarge





                SOMOVAC co-founders Esra Roan and Josh Herwig with their prototype            

                Courtesy of SOMOVAC            








 



A Memphis medical device company has raised $725,000 of seed funding almost one year after the company's founding.
SOMAVAC Medical Solutions, which designs post-surgical solutions for at-home recovery, raised the funding from two Memphis-based lead investors, Innova Memphis Inc. and MB Venture Partners, and a group of undisclosed individual investors. SOMAVAC was incorporated April 28, 2016.













 Enlarge






                            SOMOVAC co-founders Esra Roan and Josh Herwig with their prototype                        
Courtesy of SOMOVAC










 


"We are from Memphis and supported by Memphis," cofounder and CEO Esra Roan said of the investors.
The company will use the funds to complete product development and seek regulatory clearance for its wearable, post-surgical drainage device.




The device is expected to be available in 2018, pending U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) clearance.
The device is for patients who have surgeries that form large flaps in tissue layers. The SOMAVAC device is less than one inch thick and collects drainage stored in reservoirs. The device operates with the push of a button and generates a continual suction that brings tissue together. According to the founders, the device improves patients' experiences after major surgeries at home, where the longest portion of recovery takes place.
Last month, cofounder and chief technology officer Josh Herwig represented SOMAVAC during the Delta Showcase pitch competition at New Orleans Entrepreneur Week, during which the company won a $10,000 prize.
"It gave us a jolt," Roan said. "Proof we're going in the right direction."
Roan has been in biomedical research for 13 years and is an associate professor in biomedical engineering at the University of Memphis. Herwig has five years of product design, development and manufacturing experience.




 


The two met when Herwig was a graduate student of Roan’s. The two also share an alma mater, Tennessee Technological University in Cookeville.
SOMAVAC is a graduate of ZeroTo510, a Memphis-based medical device accelerator. They also participated in the 2016 Summer of Acceleration, a collaboration between EPIcenter, Memphis Bioworks and Start Co.

Elle Perry covers hospitality, tourism and health care. 













